### This article was written by psychologist Dr Jen Nash, who has type 1
It’s part of being human to eat in response to our feelings.
All kinds of emotions can compel us to eat, from unwanted moods such as
frustration, anxiety, worry or feeling down, to positive emotions like
Even neutral feelings such as boredom and apathy can be a cause to eat.
In a world where we are often surrounded by food, eating can be a common
There’s nothing wrong with using food to cope with feelings some of the time.
Food is great at regulating our emotional states, and it’s a strategy that has
been around for as long as we have.
Food has never been just about fuel for the body. Ever since you were a baby
and your tears were soothed by your caregiver's milk, food became a powerful
Is it any wonder then, that regardless of our shape and size, many of us
impulsively reach for food as a way of coping with everyday emotions? From
stress at work, to conflict in our relationships, most of us need comfort from
This becomes a problem when we find ourselves in situations where we are
experiencing feelings and, rather identifying them, our brains give us the
instruction to eat. This prevents us from normalising, expressing and managing
We tend to automatically listen to this instruction and eat - and often,
eating does actually make us feel better. It can settle us and soothe
There's nothing wrong with this - sometimes, only food will do. But, sometimes
you may benefit from strategies to identify, express and manage your emotions,
When you start to understand where your emotions are coming from, you can
start to have a new conversation with yourself when you overeat. Rather than
saying unhelpful things like "I'm greedy" or "I'm out of control", you can
For example, "I'm eating because I feel betrayed that my friend shared private
information about me" or "I'm eating because I'm cross with myself for not
Once you’ve identified the real story behind the impulse to eat, what’s next?
If someone else is causing your emotions, you may be able express your
Sometimes this isn't possible though. For example, telling an unfair boss what
you really think of them when they expect you to work overtime yet again might
So, what other ways are there to express unwanted emotions without resorting
* “I am upset at my partner because he/she forgot our anniversary”
* “I am angry with my friend as she shared something I told her in confidence”
* “I am embarrassed that I fell over at the bus stop”
* “I am cross at myself because I didn’t get my work finished’
* I am frustrated that the kids don’t keep the house tidier”
Ways to express your emotions in a risk-free way could include:
* Talking to a friend or family member
* Giving yourself permission to go off and have a cry
* Writing out what you feel, even if you tear it up afterwards
* Express yourself in a safe, physical way, such as exercise
Even if all you do for now is carry on eating, but successfully identify the
reason why, you're making an important first step.
Emotional eating can have roots in early experiences and you may need support
You can always seek support from a psychologist, counsellor or GP, who will be
Difficulties with emotional eating can be managed and getting support can be
To chat to someone about your relationship with diabetes and food, call our
